&lt;html&gt;
Perhaps the right way to go would be to submit JUnit as a JSR. You would
loose &quot;ownership&quot;, but gain acceptance, expertise and
support.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
- Yishay&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
At 09:00 PM 6/21/2001 +0000, you wrote:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;blockquote type=cite cite&gt;Here&#39;s my (admittedly limited) perspective.
Lots of people want to &lt;br&gt;
contribute to JUnit. Some people have done significant work. JXUnit 
&lt;br&gt;
went so far as forking, and Vladimir Bossicard is obviously getting 
&lt;br&gt;
frustrated (not that I blame him).&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
1. Erich and I are doing this on really limited resources, and nobody
&lt;br&gt;
has ever said, &quot;How can I help?&quot; except Erik Meade. Coming to
us with &lt;br&gt;
an offer to make some problem go away is much more likely to get a &lt;br&gt;
positive response than, &quot;Here&#39;s some code. Integrate it.&quot;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
2. JUnit as a political gesture celebrates the ability of programmers
&lt;br&gt;
to test their own software. The code and tests must be held to a &lt;br&gt;
higher standard, to demonstrate the techniques necessary to uphold &lt;br&gt;
our end of the bargain.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
3. We are new to the open source culture, and we are certain to make
&lt;br&gt;
some mistakes. When we do, we need feedback.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
4. We don&#39;t get to program much, and when we do it is generally in a
&lt;br&gt;
very constrainted situation where we have to make lots of &lt;br&gt;
compromises. Our greatest joy in JUnit is a project where we can &lt;br&gt;
engineer at the limits of our ability.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Our long-term goal is to shift primary responsibility for the further
&lt;br&gt;
development of JUnit to the community, while retaining the technical
&lt;br&gt;
excellence exhibited by junit.framework, extending that level of &lt;br&gt;
refinement to the rest of the codebase, and maintaining our ability 
&lt;br&gt;
to get together for a couple of days and add cool features.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Immediately, expect any submissions that don&#39;t come with extensive &lt;br&gt;
test cases to be unceremoniously bounced. Offers of help with grunge
&lt;br&gt;
work will be gratefully accepted.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Kent&lt;br&gt;
